For API documentation, see https://microsoft.github.io/ebpf-for-windows/
Above can be found from the main page via the "Getting Started" link which then contains the above link.
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: All development is in the source repository, and there have been no "final releases" to date.

report_responses_justification:
Acknowledgement happens by adding the "triaged" label, and any relevant comments, when the bug is discussed in a weekly meeting open to the public.
See https://github.com/microsoft/ebpf-for-windows/issues
enhancement_responses_justification:
Response happens by adding the "triaged" label, and any relevant comments, when the bug is discussed in a weekly meeting open to the public.
See https://github.com/microsoft/ebpf-for-windows/issues
build_justification: CI/CD does the build to test the steps, and https://github.com/microsoft/ebpf-for-windows/blob/main/docs/GettingStarted.md has instructions for how anyone can build.
build_floss_tools_justification: Requires Visual Studio to build Windows-specific components.   Visual Studio comes from Microsoft and so it should in a sense be trusted to the same extent as the OS that the components run on.
test_justification: Uses github workflows and the open source https://github.com/catchorg/Catch2 test framework.
test_invocation_justification: Catch2's standard way is to run the executable it generates.
test_most_justification: Automated code coverage results show 85% coverage in github CI/CD runs.
test_policy_justification:
The PR template has a section that explicitly asks about the test impact.
https://github.com/microsoft/ebpf-for-windows/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#contributing-code explicitly says:
"For all new Pull Requests the following rules apply:

Existing tests should continue to pass.
Tests need to be provided for every bug/feature that is completed.
Documentation needs to be provided for every feature that is end-user visible."

The code coverage workflow also verifies that new code has sufficient code coverage.
tests_are_added_justification: Manual review enforces this today, as can be checked by looking through recent major PRs merged.
tests_documented_added_justification:
The PR template has a section that explicitly asks about the test impact.
https://github.com/microsoft/ebpf-for-windows/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#contributing-code explicitly says:
"For all new Pull Requests the following rules apply:

Existing tests should continue to pass.
Tests need to be provided for every bug/feature that is completed.
Documentation needs to be provided for every feature that is end-user visible."
warnings_justification:
https://github.com/microsoft/ebpf-for-windows/blob/main/Analyze.default.ruleset
Warning level 4 is also applied in https://github.com/microsoft/ebpf-for-windows/blob/main/Directory.Build.props
warnings_fixed_justification:
Warning level 4 is used for MSVC code (<WarningLevel>Level4</WarningLevel>)
Warnings are treated as errors (<TreatWarningAsError>true</TreatWarningAsError>)
And the same for clang compiled files (-Werror).
warnings_strict_justification:
Warning level 4 is used for MSVC code (<WarningLevel>Level4</WarningLevel>)
Warnings are treated as errors (<TreatWarningAsError>true</TreatWarningAsError>)
See also https://github.com/microsoft/ebpf-for-windows/blob/main/Analyze.default.ruleset
crypto_call_justification: Project does not implement any cryptographic functions.
crypto_working_justification: No use of broken cryptographic algorithms.
crypto_pfs_justification: No cryptographic security mechanisms are implemented inside this project.
delivery_mitm_justification:
There have been no binary "releases" to date, but the project site uses https for source.  Project code itself does not implement any delivery mechanism.
All URLs referenced in comments in the repo are https.
static_analysis_justification:
CodeQL runs over all code.
PREVAIL verifier (https://github.com/vbpf/ebpf-verifier) runs over all ebpf program code.
"/p:Analysis='True'" is used with MSVC compiled code.
SAL annotation is used in Windows source code.
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: CodeQL does this, as does MSVC code analysis.
static_analysis_often_justification:
"/p:Analysis='True'" with MSVC runs on every commit.
CodeQL runs daily.
dynamic_analysis_justification: Fuzz testing and address sanitizer are integrated into github CI/CD workflows.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: Address sanitizer is integrated into github CI/CD workflows.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: Fuzz testing and address sanitizers do run on Debug builds with extra ASSERTs.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
english_justification:
Documentation is in English, all code comments are in English.
https://github.com/microsoft/ebpf-for-windows/issues/new/choose gives issue templates that are in English.
Also https://github.com/microsoft/ebpf-for-windows/blob/main/docs/SECURITY.md explicitly says we prefer English.
hardened_site_justification: Found all required security hardening headers.
implementation_languages: C, C++, PowerShell, Shell, Batchfile, Makefile

name: APE (Automated Pipeline Explorer)
description:
APE is a command line tool and Java API for the automated exploration of possible computational pipelines (scientific workflows) from large collections of computational tools.

APE relies on a semantic domain model that includes tool and type taxonomies as controlled vocabularies for the description of computational tools, and functional tool annotations (inputs, outputs, operations performed) using terms from these taxonomies. Based on this domain model and a specification of the available workflow inputs, the intended workflow outputs and possibly additional constraints, APE then computes possible workflows.
